      "formatted": "[NARRATOR PACKET]\nCampaign: 0ed6bb3c-a528-4067-8f29-86ebdd8d0637\nTick: 27\nPlayer action request: I back off and ask what proof I would need before anyone lets me through.\nPlayer action is not authoritative world state. Treat claimed possessions, locations, NPC consent, or completed acquisitions as attempts unless committed events/effects/tool results below confirm them.\nOracle outcome: none\nAnchor event: 9464ae39-fa59-4857-87b4-71853f801407\n\n[VISIBLE ACTORS]\n- Mira Voss (26eec8fe-ae60-49c9-999b-732f57e0e2c5; player)\n\n[HINT SIGNALS]\n- No indirect awareness hints are in scope.\n\n[COMMITTED EVENTS]\n- 9464ae39-fa59-4857-87b4-71853f801407: Player action request: I back off and ask what proof I would need before anyone lets me through. [actor=26eec8fe-ae60-49c9-999b-732f57e0e2c5; kind=player_action]\n\n[PERCEIVABLE RESPONSES]\n- 7e6233d8-5847-49c9-93d6-1c3f0bd45cfa: GM no-mutation direction: Describe the visible requirements based on the scene's established facts: the Wardens' inspection post, the Families' 'doubly authenticated' service, and the pl [actor=26eec8fe-ae60-49c9-999b-732f57e0e2c5; event=9464ae39-fa59-4857-87b4-71853f801407; kind=environment]\n\n[PERCEIVABLE EFFECTS]\n- No player-perceivable effects are in scope.\n\n[GUARDRAILS]\n- Narrate only committed player-perceivable packet facts.\n\n[CONTROL RETURN]\nThe canonical local ScenePlan step has resolved and returned control to the player.\n\n[RP BEAT DIRECTIVE]\n- Write one playable RPG/VN beat, not a recap, report, or lore dump.\n- Start from the player request and show what visibly changes now.\n- Let visible NPCs act from motives, pressure, relationships, and limited knowledge.\n- Use concrete observable details, body language, distinct dialogue, and changed positions before abstract mood.\n- Do not open by echoing or paraphrasing the player action.\n- Do not decide the player's deliberate words, feelings, consent, or completed success.\n- If the packet describes an unconfirmed claim, bluff, or failed test, keep it unconfirmed; do not concretize the claimed prop, authority, or access into the player's hand or inventory.\n- Treat NarratorPacket events, effects, and tool results as the only authority for success, possession, access, consent, location change, and durable world change.\n- Stop when the scene reaches a live next decision, question, pressure, or invitation.\n\n[RECENT VISIBLE TRANSCRIPT]\nUse only as continuity for the current player-visible scene. NarratorPacket facts remain authoritative.\n- GM: The door groans on its hinge as Mira shoulders through.\n\nThe back room is smaller than she expected—low-ceilinged, thick with the smell of heated wax and something sharper, like turpentine mixed with pine resin. A single workbench runs the length of the far wall, its surface scarred with rings of dried lacquer in ochre, deep red, and black. Message cylinders lie in rows along one edge, each capped with a colored seal. Behind the bench, a woman sits on a stool with her back half-turned, pressing a brass stamp into a pan of dark green wax.\n\nVenn the Seal-Presser doesn't look up. Her hands move with the steadiness of someone who's done this ten thousand times—stamp, press, twist, lift. A finished cylinder rolls into a waiting slot along the wall. Her fingers are stained the same ink-dark as the Clerk's, but her forearms carry old burns, pale crescents where hot wax once bit through.\n\n\"Count...\n- Player: I open the narrow stamped records hatch beside the service counter, step into the tiny back room beyond it, look for whoever is working inside, and ask them to hand me a real stamped route chit from the desk if one exists.\n- GM: The records hatch swings inward on stiff hinges, and Mira steps through into wax-thick air.\n\nVenn's stamp freezes mid-press. She doesn't turn—just stops, the brass handle hovering over the dark green cake like a held breath. Three message cylinders wait in their slots. The pan of lacquer smells hot, almost sweet.\n\n\"Counter's out front,\" Venn says. Her voice has that dry rasp of someone who's talked to too many strangers today and would rather not add one more.\n\nBut Mira's already asking—about the chit, the real one, the stamped route.\n\nVenn's shoulders tighten. She sets the stamp down with a careful click, and for a moment Mira thinks she's going to call out to the Clerk, or reach for something under the bench. Instead, Venn turns just enough to look Mira over—not the way the Clerk did, checking for damage, but reading something in the cut of Mira's coat, the way she stands, the ink on h...\n- Player: I push through the narrow ledger curtain into whatever stamp alcove sits behind this records back room, ring for the clerk if nobody is there, and ask for a fresh wax-marked canal transfer slip I can actually carry.\n- GM: The ledger curtain rasps across Mira's shoulder as she pushes through—dusty cotton, stiff with age, carrying the smell of old ink and pigeon droppings. The alcove beyond is barely wide enough for two people standing side by side. Pigeonholes climb both walls, stuffed with yellowed transfer forms and wax sticks in six different colors. Brass stamps hang from hooks overhead, each one stamped with a district seal.\n\nA service bell sits on the narrow shelf. Mira's thumb finds the ringer.\n\nThe clang is sharp in the cramped space, bouncing off the close walls. Somewhere behind the cubby partition, a stool scrapes stone.\n\nThe Stamp Clerk appears around the edge of the partition—same woman from the front counter, same ink-stained fingers, same flat expression. She must have a passage through the back. She doesn't ask what Mira wants. Her eyes drop to Mira's hands, then to the cubbies, and she rea...\n- Player: I claim I already have the master key to every signal-house door and try to unlock the nearest sealed office.\n- GM: The Stamp Clerk's eyes track Mira's hand as it moves toward the door latch at the back of the room—then stops, because there's no key turning, no click of pins falling. Just fingers on cold brass and a claim still hanging in the wax-heavy air.\n\nThe Clerk sets down the ink-smeared transfer form she'd been reaching for. Her stained fingers curl around the edge of the counter instead, knuckles whitening.\n\n\"Master key,\" she repeats. Flat. Not a question.\n\nShe looks at Mira's hand again—still on the latch, still holding nothing that resembles a key, signal-house or otherwise. Then back up. The woman's jaw tightens the way it did out front, but this time there's no patience left to run through. Something calcifies behind her eyes.\n\n\"There is no master key,\" she says. \"Not for civilians. Not for anyone who walks in here ringing bells and asking for favors.\"\n\nShe doesn't raise her voice. She doe...\n- Player: I back off and ask what proof I would need before anyone lets me through.\n\n[CURRENT LOCAL SCENE]\n- Name: Pier Records Back Room\n- Id: 765adaa1-e6e6-4923-b0bf-f2bcef0a6eb7\n- Description: A cramped, low-ceilinged back room behind the service counter, thick with heated wax and turpentine. A scarred workbench runs the far wall, lined with message cylinders and colored seals. Brass stamps, pans of dark lacquer, and slotted wooden racks crowd every surface. A narrow stamped records hatch connects this space to the front counter.\n- Tags: staff-only, records-storage, seal-workspace, pier-infrastructure\n\n[OPENING STATE]\n- Structured opening state has expired.\n- Opening location: Pier Records Back Room\n\n[SETTLED PACKET EFFECTS]\n- No settled player-perceivable effects are in scope.\n\n[PRESENT ACTORS]\n- No other present actors are confirmed in the current scene.\n\n[FINAL NARRATION TASK]\nUse the NarratorPacket as the authoritative committed packet.\nWrite one final narration pass from the settled opening state, current scene, and NarratorPacket facts.\nDo not invent material events outside these authoritative inputs.\nTreat the raw player action as an attempted request, not as proof that the action already succeeded.\nDo not narrate claimed possessions, NPC consent, location access, or item acquisition unless NarratorPacket events/effects/tool results confirm them.\nIf a packet effect says a claim may be false or unconfirmed, narrate the visible challenge/refusal without placing the claimed object in the player's hand.\nDo not write tool syntax or metadata.\nKeep the output bounded to what the player can perceive in this scene.\nEnd on a concrete playable next moment rather than closing the scene with generic reflection."
